Review_body:
I've seen many people disliking my review and I've seen your main complaints. You don't need to change your opinion but I will try to back mine and explain why I don't have much to grumble about:
1. it is slow-paced and thus boring (I've lately watched Paris, Texas, First Man and other pretty slow-paced movies and since I also watch such movies on a regular basis, I have crafted myself an iron sense of patience; also, when I get bored, I try to analyze character psychologically or think about how I'd have felt if I were in their stead. This keeps my mind busy. Still, the slow-pacing and slow build-up is the main reason for which I lowered the score. I agree with you but it just wasn't too slow to mar my experience);
2. It resembles The Wicker Man from 73' (I haven't seen the movie yet, though I know the trope you're all talking about, the one that makes the movie ''unoriginal''. And perhaps the core idea is indeed hackneyed, but I find the way Midsommar is executed to be thrilling - that if you live in the present and you're not thinking ''I know what is going to happen and thus I have already ruined my movie-going experience'' once every two seconds);
3. It is inhumanly gruesome and brutal. ( A Clockwork Orange, Saving Private Ryan, Downfall and many other movies are frankly no less brutal than this. );
4. Expectations. Here you have won. I think this should be the true reason for which one would not like Midsommar: different expectations. I began watching it in hope of something fremd, out of the ordinary. I wasn't in for the jump-scares, I wanted to be shown a new way of getting chills and that's what I got.As I said, if you expect plenty of jump-scares, fake scares and gore to make your blood rush or your face green, your expectations will be accomplished to a certain degree, but I warn you : the main thrust here is building psychological dread and feelings of uneasiness in your stomach and mind. It is not the everyday horror movie you see at cinema, for it relies heavily on characters' traumas, feelings of guilt, shame, repression and isolation.I think Florence Pugh was the right choice for the role, as she has a talent in playing characters who are grieving or simply hiding parts of themselves deep inside, so as nobody can see their real pain and weakness (like she does when playing ''Amy March'' in Greta Gerwig's ''Little Women'' adaptation). I haven't seen Ari Aster's ''Hereditary'' to this day, but be sure I will, because here he proves that he ''knows business'' with that unique camerawork and his ''reality disintegrating/blurring effect''. The soundtrack is also suitable.A 9,30 out of 10 from me.
